SIMPLE: fulsome
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fulsome
<hw>Ful"some</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Full</ets>, a.
+ <ets>-some</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Full; abundant; plenteous;
not shriveled.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His lean, pale, hoar, and withered corpse grew <qex>fulsome</qex>,
fair, and fresh.</q> <rj><qau>Golding.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Offending or disgusting by overfullness, excess, or
grossness; cloying; gross; nauseous; esp., offensive from excess of
praise; <as>as, <ex>fulsome</ex> flattery</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And lest the <qex>fulsome</qex> artifice should fail⟦br⟧
Themselves will hide its coarseness with a veil.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Lustful; wanton; obscene; also, tending to
obscenity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Fulsome ewes.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Ful"some*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Ful"some*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fulvid</ent>⟦br⟧
